var definitions = ['<h2>Nochmals vielen Dank für das Essen, es war köstlich.</h2><div><strong>Nochmals</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "once again" or "another time". It is used here to repeat thanks or emphasize gratitude.</div><div><strong>vielen</strong> This is the inflected form of the German adjective "viel", meaning "many" or "much". When used with "Dank", it means "many thanks" or "much appreciation".</div><div><strong>Dank</strong> This is a German noun meaning "thanks" or "thank you". It is often used in the phrase "vielen Dank" to express gratitude.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "for" in English, indicating the recipient or beneficiary of gratitude in this context.</div><div><strong>das Essen</strong> This phrase means "the meal" or "the food" in German. "Das" is the neutral article "the", and "Essen" is the noun "meal" or "food".</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person neuter singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. In this sentence, it refers back to the meal mentioned earlier.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It indicates the state of being in the past.</div><div><strong>köstlich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "delicious". It describes the quality of the meal that was enjoyed.</div>','<h2>Kein Problem! Es ist mir ein Vergnügen!</h2><div><strong>Kein</strong> This is the German word for "no" or "none". It is a combination of "kein" (no) and "Problem" (problem), negating the existence of a problem, hence "no problem".</div><div><strong>Problem!</strong> This is the German noun for "problem". It is being negated in this sentence by "kein", which together express the phrase "No problem!" commonly used as an informal response to thanks or to indicate that something is not an issue.</div><div><strong>Es</strong> This translates to "it" in English, and it is the third-person singular pronoun used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". The verb connects the subject "Es" (it) to the predicate "mir ein Vergnügen" (a pleasure to me).</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the dative form of the first-person singular pronoun "ich", meaning "to me" or "for me". It indicates the indirect object of the sentence, meaning the pleasure is given to the speaker.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the German indefinite article for the accusative masculine "ein" or nominative neuter "ein", which translates to "a" or "an" in English. It is part of the predicate "ein Vergnügen".</div><div><strong>Vergnügen!</strong> This is a German noun meaning "pleasure" or "delight". The full sentence thus means "It is a pleasure for me", indicating that the speaker is happy to do something or that something pleases the speaker.</div>','<h2>Das Wetter ist heute wirklich schön!</h2><div><strong>Das</strong> This is the neuter definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here to specify a particular thing, in this case, the weather.</div><div><strong>Wetter</strong> This is a neuter noun in German meaning "weather". In this sentence, it’s the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject "Das Wetter" with the adjective "schön" to describe the state of the weather.</div><div><strong>heute</strong> This is an adverb meaning "today". It indicates the time when the weather is being described as "schön".</div><div><strong>wirklich</strong> This is an adverb meaning "really" or "actually". It is used to emphasize the adjective "schön".</div><div><strong>schön</strong> This is an adjective meaning "beautiful" or "nice". In the context of this sentence, it’s describing the weather as being pleasurable or enjoyable.</div>','<h2>Ja, es ist ein schöner Tag! Perfektes Wetter!</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It affirms or agrees with something previously mentioned or asked.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It is used as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject with the complement of the predicate, indicating a state of being or condition.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German which can be translated to "a" or "an" in English. It introduces a non-specific noun, in this case "schöner Tag".</div><div><strong>schöner</strong> This is the nominative masculine form of the German adjective "schön", meaning "beautiful" or "nice". It is used here to modify "Tag" (day), and it takes the -er ending because "Tag" is masculine and in the nominative case due to being the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Tag</strong> This is a masculine noun in German meaning "day". It is the subject of the clause and is described by the adjective "schöner". It takes a capital letter as all German nouns are capitalized.</div><div><strong>Perfektes</strong> This is the nominative neuter form of the German adjective "perfekt", meaning "perfect". It is used here to describe "Wetter". In German, the adjective takes the -es ending to agree with the neuter gender and nominative case. Since this is a one-word exclamation, "perfektes" serves as both the subject and the predicate adjective due to ellipsis.</div><div><strong>Wetter</strong> This is a neuter noun in German meaning "weather". As an exclamation, it’s understood from the context that the speaker is exclaiming about the perfect state of the weather, effectively saying "The weather [is] perfect!" German nouns are always capitalized.</div>','<h2>Ich habe wirklich Glück an meinem ersten Tag.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or in this case, experiencing something.</div><div><strong>wirklich</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "really" or "truly". It is used to emphasize the statement that follows.</div><div><strong>Glück</strong> This is a German noun meaning "luck" or "fortune". In this sentence, it is the direct object, indicating what the subject has.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a German preposition that can mean "on" or "at" depending on the context. It indicates the relationship between "Glück" and the time expression that follows.</div><div><strong>meinem</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the dative case, masculine singular form of "mein", which means "my". It indicates that the day is related to the speaker.</div><div><strong>ersten</strong> This is an ordinal number in German, meaning "first". It describes the day and is used as an adjective in this case.</div><div><strong>Tag</strong> This is a German noun meaning "day". Combined with "an meinem ersten", it specifies the time frame in which the speaker has luck.</div>','<h2>Ja, du hast Glück. Am Montag hat es geregnet.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It confirms or agrees with a statement.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence here.</div><div><strong>hast</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or a state of being.</div><div><strong>Glück</strong> This is a German noun meaning "luck" or "fortune". Here, it indicates that the person addressed is considered fortunate.</div><div><strong>Am</strong> This is a prepositional phrase in German, combining the preposition "an" ("on" relating to days) with the masculine or neuter definite article "dem", together meaning "on the" when referring to a specific date or day.</div><div><strong>Montag</strong> This is the German word for "Monday". It’s a masculine noun.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "haben", utilized here as an auxiliary verb to form the perfect tense.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is a neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s often used as a placeholder subject in sentences.</div><div><strong>geregnet</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "regnen", which means "to rain". Combined with "hat", it forms the perfect tense, indicating that it rained.</div>','<h2>Oh nein! Es hat geregnet?</h2><div><strong>Oh</strong> This is an interjection in German expressing surprise, disappointment, or frustration, similar to "oh" in English.</div><div><strong>nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It is often used to respond negatively to a question or to express disappointment.</div><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It is the subject of the sentence, referring to the weather or the situation implicitly.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present perfect tense conjugation of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this context, it forms part of the present perfect tense "hat geregnet" (has rained).</div><div><strong>geregnet</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "regnen", which means "to rain". Used with "hat", it forms the present perfect tense, indicating a past action that has relevance to the present ("has rained").</div><div><strong>?</strong> The question mark at the end indicates that this sentence is a question, reflecting surprise or disbelief that it has rained.</div>','<h2>Um genau zu sein, war es die ganze Woche über bewölkt und kalt.</h2><div><strong>Um</strong> This is a German preposition meaning "around" but in this context, it sets off a phrase which provides clarification and means "to be precise" or "strictly speaking". It often leads into a more detailed explanation.</div><div><strong>genau</strong> This is an adjective meaning "exact" or "precise" in English. In combination with "um" it forms the phrase "to be exact" or "precisely".</div><div><strong>zu sein,</strong> Is the infinitive form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". The "zu" indicates the infinitive and is often equivalent to the English "to" before a verb. This whole phrase "um genau zu sein" is a common set phrase in German.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the simple past tense of the verb "sein", meaning "was". It indicates the state of the weather in the past.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neutral pronoun "it" referring in this case to the weather.</div><div><strong>die ganze Woche</strong> This means "the whole week" with "die" being the feminine definite article in the nominative case, "ganze" meaning "whole" or "entire", and "Woche" meaning "week".</div><div><strong>über</strong> This is a preposition that can mean "over", "above", or, in this context, "during".</div><div><strong>bewölkt</strong> This is an adjective meaning "cloudy". It describes the weather over the course of the week.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This is the German conjunction meaning "and", used to connect words, phrases, and clauses.</div><div><strong>kalt.</strong> This adjective means "cold". Like "bewölkt", it describes the weather conditions.</div>','<h2>Das ist schade... Hat es geschneit?</h2><div><strong>Das</strong> This is a neuter definite article in German, meaning "the". It also can be used as a demonstrative pronoun, equivalent to "that" in English.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It shows the state of being.</div><div><strong>schade</strong> This is a German interjection expressing regret or pity, corresponding to "too bad" or "what a shame" in English.</div><div>The ellipsis "..." indicates a pause or trail off in thought, representing possible emotion or contemplation in the statement.</div><div><strong>Hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present perfect tense of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". In a question, it starts the formation of the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neuter third-person singular pronoun in German, meaning "it".</div><div><strong>geschneit</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "schneien", meaning "to snow". Used here with "hat", it forms the present perfect tense, asking if it has snowed.</div>','<h2>Schnee? Nein! Zu dieser Jahreszeit schneit es nicht!</h2><div><strong>Schnee</strong> This is the German word for "snow". It’s a noun in the nominative case used here as an exclamation or a subject of conversation.</div><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>Zu dieser Jahreszeit</strong> This phrase means "at this time of year". "Zu" can be translated as "at" or "during" when referring to time, "dieser" is the demonstrative pronoun "this", and "Jahreszeit" means "season of the year".</div><div><strong>schneit</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "schneien", which means "to snow". It indicates occurrence or action.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person neutral pronoun "it" in German. It serves as the subject for impersonal verbs like "schneien".</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This word is the adverb "not" in English. It negates the verb, stating that something does not happen or is not the case.</div>','<h2>Oh! Aber so kalt war es dann doch nicht...</h2><div><strong>Oh!</strong> This is an exclamation, expressing a range of emotions from surprise to disappointment. It’s similar to its English equivalent "Oh!"</div><div><strong>Aber</strong> This is the German conjunction for "but". It’s used to present a contrast or exception.</div><div><strong>so</strong> This is an adverb meaning "so" or "thus" in English. It’s often used for emphasis or to describe the manner or degree of something.</div><div><strong>kalt</strong> This is an adjective meaning "cold". In the sentence, it describes the temperature or weather condition.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the past tense, first and third-person singular form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It signifies a past state of being.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person neutral pronoun "it" in English. It is the subject of the sentence, referring to the weather or temperature.</div><div><strong>dann</strong> This adverb means "then" and is used to refer to a point in time relative to a previously mentioned event or context.</div><div><strong>doch</strong> This particle is often difficult to translate directly but generally serves to intensify or affirm the statement. It could be seen as a reinforcement, which in this context could be translated as "after all" or "however".</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the adverb for "not" negating a statement.</div>','<h2>Es war kalt für Deutschland! Nicht für den Nordpol!</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the personal pronoun "it" in German, used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the past tense (imperfect) of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It describes the state of being in the past.</div><div><strong>kalt</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "cold". It is used here to describe the temperature or weather conditions.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a preposition in German that means "for". It indicates the benefit or suitability for something or someone.</div><div><strong>Deutschland</strong> This is a proper noun, the name of the country "Germany" in German.</div><div><strong>Nicht</strong> This is the German word for "not". It is used here to negate the following phrase, creating a contrast.</div><div><strong>für den</strong> The preposition "für" combined with the article "den" (the masculine singular accusative form of "the") indicates "for the" in reference to a specific place.</div><div><strong>Nordpol</strong> This is a proper noun, the German word for "North Pole". It refers to the point in the Northern Hemisphere where the Earth’s axis of rotation meets its surface.</div>','<h2>Ja, nun, es hat in Calgary geschneit, als ich abgeflogen bin.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It’s often used to confirm something or to signal agreement.</div><div><strong>nun</strong> This German word is an adverb often used to mean "now" or "well", indicating a transition or contemplation in the conversation.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s often used as a placeholder subject in sentences.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present perfect tense of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It’s used here as an auxiliary verb to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>in Calgary</strong> "In Calgary" specifies the location where the action took place. Calgary is a city in Canada.</div><div><strong>geschneit</strong> This is the past participle of "schneien", which means "to snow". This is the main verb in this clause, denoting the action that took place.</div><div><strong>als</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German that means "when" or "as". It introduces a time clause.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>abgeflogen</strong> This is the past participle of the separable verb "abfliegen", which means "to take off" in the context of flight. Combined with "bin", it indicates the past tense.</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". Here, it’s used with the past participle "abgeflogen" to form the present perfect tense.</div>','<h2>Du machst Witze! Für dich ist das also der Sommer?</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the German pronoun for "you" in the second-person singular nominative case. It’s used when addressing one person informally.</div><div><strong>machst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "machen", which means "to do" or "to make". In this context, it translates to "make" or "do" as in "You make jokes".</div><div><strong>Witze</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Witz", which means "joke" in English. The phrase "Du machst Witze" literally means "You make jokes" or more idiomatically "You’re kidding" or "You’re joking".</div><div><strong>Für</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "for" in English. It’s used here to indicate the subject or person for whom a particular situation or action is intended or true.</div><div><strong>dich</strong> This is the German pronoun for "you" in the accusative case. It’s the direct or indirect object form of "du", used here after the preposition "für".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. In this sentence, it indicates a state of being or existence.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is a German demonstrative pronoun that translates as "that" or "this" in English, depending on context. It is used here as the subject of the sentence, referring back to a specific thing or situation presumably known to both the speaker and listener.</div><div><strong>also</strong> This is an adverb meaning "thus", "so", or "therefore" in English. It often indicates a conclusion or inference drawn from something mentioned before.</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the definite article for masculine singular nouns in the nominative case, which translates to "the" in English. It is used here before the word "Sommer" which is masculine.</div><div><strong>Sommer?</strong> This is the German word for "summer". It is used here to refer to the season, which the speaker apparently finds ironically referred to or unsuitably characterized by the current weather or situation.</div>','<h2>So ziemlich. Wie war das Wetter in San Francisco?</h2><div><strong>So</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "so" or "thus" in English. It is often used to express manner or degree.</div><div><strong>ziemlich</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "quite" or "fairly" in English. It’s used to describe the extent of something.</div><div><strong>Wie</strong> This is the German word for "how" or "what". It’s used to ask questions about the nature, condition, or quality of something.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the past tense of the German verb "sein", which means "to be". Here, it’s the third-person singular past tense, meaning "was" in English.</div><div><strong>das Wetter</strong> This is a German noun phrase meaning "the weather". "Das" is the neutral definite article in nominative case, and "Wetter" is the neutral noun for "weather".</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a German preposition equivalent to "in" in English, indicating location or place.</div><div><strong>San Francisco</strong> This is a proper noun, a city in the United States. In German, as in English, the names of cities do not get translated.</div>','<h2>Wie üblich. Etwa neunzehn Grad Celsius.</h2><div><strong>Wie</strong> This is the German word for "how" or "as". In this context, it implies "as" or "like", used to describe something that is typical or usual.</div><div><strong>üblich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "usual" or "customary". It describes something that is done according to a habit or tradition.</div><div><strong>Etwa</strong> This means "approximately" or "about" in German. It’s used to indicate that the next number is an estimate.</div><div><strong>neunzehn</strong> This is the German word for the number nineteen. It’s used here to specify the estimated number.</div><div><strong>Grad</strong> This word means "degrees" in German. It signifies the unit of measurement for temperature.</div><div><strong>Celsius</strong> This refers to the Celsius scale, a temperature scale used to measure degrees Celsius. This term is the same in both German and English and is used worldwide to express temperature.</div>','<h2>Ach ja? Ich dachte, in Kalifornien sei es sehr warm.</h2><div><strong>Ach</strong> This is an interjection commonly used in German to express a variety of emotions such as realization, remembrance, or resignation. Here, it reflects a recognition or mild surprise.</div><div><strong>ja?</strong> This is the German word for "yes", often used as a tag question to express interest or ask for confirmation, similar to "right?" or "isn’t it?" in English.</div><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>dachte</strong> This is the first-person singular simple past tense form of the verb "denken", which means "to think". In this sentence, it is used to indicate a past belief or thought.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition which denotes location or position, similar to "in" in English. It introduces the place being discussed.</div><div><strong>Kalifornien</strong> This is the German name for "California", a state in the United States, and is the object of the preposition "in".</div><div><strong>sei</strong> This is the third-person singular subjunctive form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". The subjunctive mood is used here to express uncertainty, doubt, or a condition contrary to fact.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English, and is the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in English, used for emphasis and intensifying the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>warm</strong> This is an adjective meaning "warm", and it describes the temperature or weather condition being attributed to California.</div>','<h2>Nicht da, wo ich wohne! Es wird nie sehr warm.</h2><div><strong>Nicht</strong> This is the German word for "not" or "no" in English. It is used here to negate the statement that follows.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is the German word for "there". In this context, it implies "that place" or "where" referring to somewhere else, but not the speaker’s location.</div><div><strong>wo</strong> This is the German word for "where". It introduces a relative clause referring to a place or location.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the relative clause.</div><div><strong>wohne</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "wohnen", which means "to live" or "to reside". Here it conveys where the speaker lives.</div><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German neuter pronoun "it", used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wird</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "werden", which means "to become" or, when used as an auxiliary verb, forms the future tense. In this case, it is used to describe a future condition (of the weather).</div><div><strong>nie</strong> This is the German word for "never". It is used to indicate that something does not happen at any time.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is the German word for "very". It is an intensifier used here to strengthen the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>warm</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "warm". It describes temperature and, when used here, it implies that it never gets very warm where the speaker lives.</div>','<h2>Das ist schade... Schneit es jemals?</h2><div><strong>Das</strong> This is the German definite article for neutral nouns in the nominative case, and translates as "the" in English. Here, it’s used as a demonstrative pronoun meaning "that".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It indicates existence or a state of being.</div><div><strong>schade</strong> This is a German interjection meaning "too bad" or "what a pity". Here, it’s used to express regret or disappointment.</div><div><strong>Schneit</strong> This comes from the German verb "schneien", which means "to snow". It is conjugated in the third-person singular present indicative, meaning "it snows" or "is it snowing". </div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the German pronoun for "it" in the nominative case, representing an unspecified or neutral object or subject, often used with the weather.</div><div><strong>jemals</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "ever". It’s used to inquire about the occurrence of an event at any time in the past or future.</div>','<h2>Nein, kein Schnee. Es wird auch nie sehr kalt.</h2><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>kein</strong> This is a negating article in German, roughly translating to "no" or "not any" in English. It is used to negate a noun, indicating the absence of something and is used instead of "nicht ein(e)" (not a).</div><div><strong>Schnee</strong> This is the German noun for "snow". It’s in the nominative case as it is the subject of the negated noun phrase initiated by "kein".</div><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German third-person neuter pronoun "it", similar to English. Here, it’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wird</strong> This is the third-person singular form of the verb "werden", which means "to become" or as a helping verb indicating the future tense in English.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is the German word for "also" or "too". It is used to add information to the sentence, implying that the absence of snow is not the only weather characteristic.</div><div><strong>nie</strong> This is the German word for "never". It’s an adverb used to describe the frequency of an event, indicating that something does not happen at any time.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is the German word for "very". It’s an adverb used to intensify adjectives or other adverbs.</div><div><strong>kalt</strong> This German adjective means "cold". In this sentence, it is used predicatively in combination with "sehr" to state that it never becomes very cold.</div>','<h2>Und weißt du, ob es morgen schön draußen wird?</h2><div><strong>Und</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "and". It is used to connect sentences or clauses.</div><div><strong>weißt</strong> This comes from the German verb "wissen", meaning "to know". "Weißt" is the second-person singular present tense, so it means "you know".</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English.</div><div><strong>ob</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "whether" or "if". It is used to introduce an indirect question or a conditional clause.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It is often used as a placeholder subject.</div><div><strong>morgen</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "tomorrow".</div><div><strong>schön</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "beautiful" or "nice". In this context, it refers to the weather being good.</div><div><strong>draußen</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "outside".</div><div><strong>wird</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the German verb "werden", meaning "to become" or "will be" when used as a helping verb in future tense.</div>','<h2>Ich weiß nicht, ich habe mir den Wetterbericht für morgen nicht angesehen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>weiß</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know". It indicates that the speaker has knowledge about something, or, in this case, is used with "nicht" to express the lack of knowledge or uncertainty.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not". It negates a statement or indicates the absence of something.</div><div><strong>ich habe</strong> This is a combination of "ich", the first-person singular pronoun, and "habe", which is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this context, it’s used to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular reflexive pronoun in the dative case in German. It’s used reflexively here to indicate that the action of the verb affects the speaker themselves.</div><div><strong>den Wetterbericht</strong> This phrase is made up of the article "den" (the, masculine accusative) and the noun "Wetterbericht", which means "weather report". Together, this is the direct object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>für morgen</strong> This is a prepositional phrase that consists of the preposition "für", meaning "for", and "morgen", which means "tomorrow". It indicates the time frame for the weather report.</div><div><strong>nicht angesehen</strong> This is the past participle "angesehen", of the verb "ansehen", which means "to look at" or "to watch", combined with "nicht" to indicate that the action has not been performed. "Angesehen" is placed at the end of the clause in the perfect tense construction in German.</div>','<h2>Ich sehe mir mal den Wetterbericht auf meinem Handy an.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sehe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sehen", which means "to see". Here, it suggests the action of looking or watching.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the dative case. In German, reflexive verbs can sometimes use the dative reflexive pronoun for emphasis or to indicate an action done for one’s own benefit. In this sentence, it can be understood as "for myself".</div><div><strong>mal</strong> This is a modal particle used in German to soften the tone of the statement or suggest a casual, non-committal action. It’s often translated as "just", "for a moment", or "once".</div><div><strong>den Wetterbericht</strong> This is a noun phrase consisting of the definite article "den" (the, accusative masculine singular) and "Wetterbericht", which means "weather report". It’s the direct object of the sentence, indicating what is being seen.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition which means "on" in English. It is used here to indicate the medium or platform on which the action is taking place ("on my phone").</div><div><strong>meinem Handy</strong> This is a possessive construction that includes <strong>meinem</strong>, which means "my" (dative masculine/neuter singular), and <strong>Handy</strong>, which is a German word for "mobile phone" or "cell phone". The phrase constructs the phrase "on my phone".</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a separable prefix verb particle. In German, some verbs come with a separable prefix that can move to the end of the sentence or clause. Here, the particle "an" is separated from "sehen", making up the phrasal verb "ansehen", which means "to look at" or "to watch".</div>','<h2>Ja, das ist eine gute Idee.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It indicates agreement or affirmation to a statement or question.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the neuter singular article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It also serves as a demonstrative pronoun here, translating to "that".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject ("das").</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, in the feminine or neuter nominative and accusative singular form. It is equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>gute</strong> This is the feminine/neuter nominative/accusative singular form of the German adjective "gut", which means "good" in English. It describes the noun "Idee".</div><div><strong>Idee</strong> This is a feminine noun in German meaning "idea". In the sentence, it is the object being described as "good".</div>','<h2>Es wird ein bisschen windig, aber morgen gibt es keinen Regen!</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German pronoun for "it", functioning as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wird</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "werden", which is being used here to form the future tense, meaning "will be".</div><div><strong>ein bisschen</strong> This is a German phrase meaning "a little" or "a bit", which is used here to describe the extent of the wind.</div><div><strong>windig</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "windy".</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is the German word for "but", used as a conjunction to connect contrasting clauses.</div><div><strong>morgen</strong> This is the German word for "tomorrow".</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "geben", which means "to give". In this context, it’s used to state that something exists or occurs (there is/there are).</div><div><strong>es</strong> This represents "it" or "there’" in English, used here with "gibt" to form the expression "es gibt", meaning "there is/there are".</div><div><strong>keinen</strong> This is the negative article for masculine nouns in the accusative case, meaning "no" or "not any". </div><div><strong>Regen</strong> This is the German word for "rain", which is a masculine noun in the nominative and accusative case.</div>','<h2>Das ist gut. Allerdings reise ich morgen früh ab.</h2><div><strong>Das</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun, similar to "that" or "this" in English, used here to refer to a previously mentioned thing or situation.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>gut</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "good". It’s used here to express approval or satisfaction.</div><div><strong>Allerdings</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "however" or "nevertheless". It introduces a contrast or limitation to what has been said before.</div><div><strong>reise</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "reisen", which means "to travel" in English. In this sentence, it indicates the speaker’s imminent action.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>morgen</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "tomorrow". It indicates the time when the action (traveling) will take place.</div><div><strong>früh</strong> This is a German adjective used here as an adverb meaning "early". It modifies the time of the action further, indicating the travel is early in the morning.</div><div><strong>ab</strong> This is a German separable prefix used with the verb "reise" that means "away" or "off" in this context. When combined with "reisen", it suggests departure. It’s also a preposition but is used here as part of the verb "abreisen", which means "to depart" or "leave".</div>','<h2>Wirklich? Du fliegst zurück nach Hause?</h2><div><strong>Wirklich?</strong> This is the German adverb meaning "really" or "actually". It’s often used to express surprise or to question the veracity of a statement.</div><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used to directly address the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>fliegst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "fliegen", which means "to fly". It denotes the action being performed by the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>zurück</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "back" or "return". When combined with verbs of movement, it indicates a return to a previous location.</div><div><strong>nach</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "to", "towards", or "after". It’s used here to express a direction or a target destination.</div><div><strong>Hause</strong> This is the German word for "home". "Nach Hause" is a fixed phrase that means "to (the) home" or "homeward". Unlike the English "home", the German "Hause" is used with the preposition "nach" to indicate direction.</div>','<h2>Ja, es war nur eine kurze Reise. Ich vermisse meine Familie.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It is often used to acknowledge or confirm the preceding statement.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence here.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It describes a past state of being or condition.</div><div><strong>nur</strong> This German word translates to "only" or "just" in English. It’s an adverb used to minimize or limit the extent of something.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is the indefinite article in German for feminine or plural nouns in the nominative or accusative case, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. Here, it is used with the feminine noun "Reise".</div><div><strong>kurze</strong> This is the German adjective "kurz" in its inflected form to match the feminine singular noun "Reise" in the accusative case. It means "short".</div><div><strong>Reise</strong> This is a feminine German noun meaning "trip" or "journey".</div><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the second sentence.</div><div><strong>vermisse</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "vermissen", which means "to miss" in German. It indicates the action of feeling the absence of someone or something.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German equivalent to "my" in English. It is used here in its feminine plural form to match the noun "Familie".</div><div><strong>Familie</strong> This is a feminine German noun meaning "family".</div>','<h2>Dann lass uns den Rest des Tages genießen.</h2><div><strong>Dann</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "then" or "afterward". It often indicates the next step in a sequence of events.</div><div><strong>lass</strong> This is the imperative form of "lassen", meaning "let" or "allow". In this context, it’s used like the English imperative "let’s" for suggesting an action to be taken by us or "let us".</div><div><strong>uns</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "us". It’s in the accusative case and is the object of the verb "lassen".</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is a definite article in the accusative case for masculine nouns in German. It translates to "the".</div><div><strong>Rest</strong> This German noun means "rest" or "remainder". Here, it’s being used to refer to the remaining part of something, in the accusative case due to the grammatical structure of the sentence.</div><div><strong>des</strong> This is a possessive/genitive article in German, equivalent to "of the" in English. It indicates a relationship of belonging between "Rest" and "Tages".</div><div><strong>Tages</strong> This is the genitive singular form of "Tag", which means "day" in English. The genitive case is used here to show possession, so "des Tages" translates to "of the day".</div><div><strong>genießen</strong> This is the infinitive form of a German verb meaning "to enjoy". In the structure of the sentence, it joins with "lass uns" to form the suggestion "let’s enjoy".</div>','<h2>Wo willst du jetzt hingehen?</h2><div><strong>Wo</strong> This is the German word for "where". It’s used to ask the location or destination.</div><div><strong>willst</strong> This comes from the German modal verb "wollen" which means "to want". "Willst" is the second-person singular present tense, thus it means "you want".</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>jetzt</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "now". It indicates the time at which the action is taking place.</div><div><strong>hingehen</strong> This is a separable verb in German that combines "hin" meaning "to there" and "gehen" meaning "to go". Together, "hingehen" means to go to a certain place. In the context of the sentence, it’s in the infinitive form, used after the modal verb "willst".</div>','<h2>Ich finde, du solltest es aussuchen. Es ist dein letzter Tag.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>finde</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "finden", which means "to find" or "to think". In this context, it means "I think" or "I find".</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here to directly address the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>solltest</strong> This is the second-person singular past tense form of the modal verb "sollen", which means "should" or "ought to". Here, it suggests a recommendation or advice.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neuter third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the direct object of the sentence, referring to something that is supposed to be selected.</div><div><strong>aussuchen</strong> This is the infinitive form of a separable verb, which means "to choose" or "to pick out". The prefix "aus-" separates and goes to the end of the clause when conjugated.</div><div><strong>Es</strong> Again, this is the neuter third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the second sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject in this sentence.</div><div><strong>dein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German in the second-person singular, equivalent to "your" in English. It indicates possession or association with the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>letzter</strong> This is an adjective in German that means "last". It is declined to match "Tag", which is masculine and singular in this context.</div><div><strong>Tag</strong> This is a noun in German which means "day". It is masculine and singular here and it’s the subject of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Oh, nein! Ist schon in Ordnung! Du kannst es aussuchen!</h2><div><strong>Oh</strong> This is an interjection used in German to express a variety of emotions such as surprise, disappointment, or realization, similar to "oh" in English.</div><div><strong>nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>Ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It indicates the state or existence of the subject.</div><div><strong>schon</strong> This is an adverb in German that can mean "already" or can be used for reassurance, often translated as "alright" or "okay" in this context.</div><div><strong>in Ordnung</strong> This phrase translates to "in order" in English, meaning something is alright, acceptable, or not a problem.</div><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence here.</div><div><strong>kannst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "können", which means "can" or "to be able to". It indicates ability or permission.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neuter singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the direct object in the sentence, referring to something previously mentioned.</div><div><strong>aussuchen</strong> This is a separable prefix verb in German which means "to choose" or "to select". The prefix "aus-" conveys the meaning of selecting from a range of options.</div>','<h2>Nein, nur zu! Du kannst es aussuchen! Ich bestehe darauf.</h2><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It is used to negate a statement or to disagree with a question or suggestion.</div><div><strong>nur zu</strong> This phrase means "go ahead" or "please do" in English. It is used to encourage someone to proceed with an action.</div><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>kannst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "können", which means "can" or "to be able to". It indicates ability or possibility.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is a neutral-gender third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It is the direct object of the verb "aussuchen".</div><div><strong>aussuchen</strong> This is a separable prefix verb in German that means "to choose" or "to pick out". It is used here in the imperative form, giving a command or an invitation to the second-person singular.</div><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the second sentence.</div><div><strong>bestehe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "bestehen", which can mean "to insist", "to persist", or "to comprise". Here, it means "to insist".</div><div><strong>darauf</strong> This is a pronominal adverb in German that combines the preposition "auf" with the pronoun "dar", essentially meaning "on that" or "upon it". It’s used here to emphasize what the speaker is insisting on.</div>','<h2>Naja, ich habe das Brandenburger Tor noch nie an einem sonnigen Tag gesehen...</h2><div><strong>Naja</strong> This is a German interjection similar to "well" or "so" in English. It’s often used to express hesitation or to preface a remark.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It is used here to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is a definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here in the neuter singular form to refer to "Brandenburger Tor".</div><div><strong>Brandenburger Tor</strong> This is a proper noun referring to the Brandenburg Gate, a famous historical monument in Berlin, Germany. In the sentence, it’s the direct object of the verb "habe gesehen".</div><div><strong>noch</strong> This is an adverb meaning "still" or "yet" in English. In this context, it is used to express that the action has not occurred up until this point.</div><div><strong>nie</strong> This is an adverb meaning "never" in English. It negates the action, indicating that the speaker has never seen the Brandenburg Gate on a sunny day.</div><div><strong>an einem</strong> This phrase is made up of the preposition "an", which can mean "on" among other things, and the indefinite article "einem", which is masculine/neuter dative singular of "ein" (a/an). It is used here to indicate a time when something has not happened.</div><div><strong>sonnigen</strong> This is the adjective "sonnig" in the masculine/neuter dative singular form, which means "sunny". It describes the kind of day the speaker has not seen the Brandenburg Gate.</div><div><strong>Tag</strong> This is a masculine noun that means "day" in English. In the sentence, it’s the object of the preposition "an" and together with "an einem sonnigen" forms the phrase "on a sunny day".</div><div><strong>gesehen</strong> This is the past participle of "sehen", which means "to see". It is used with the auxiliary verb "habe" to form the present perfect tense, expressing the completed action of seeing (or in this case, not seeing).</div><div><strong>...</strong> These ellipsis dots indicate that the sentence is trailing off or that there is more to the speaker’s thought that has not been expressed.</div>','<h2>Perfekt! Sehen wir uns also das Brandenburger Tor an!</h2><div><strong>Perfekt!</strong> This is a German exclamatory word meaning "Perfect!". It reflects approval or enthusiasm about something.</div><div><strong>Sehen</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the German verb "sehen", which means "to see". In the context of this sentence, it’s the imperative "let’s see".</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>uns</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the first-person plural, equivalent to "ourselves" in English. It’s used reflexively with the verb "sehen" to signify "let’s look at" or "let’s see".</div><div><strong>also</strong> This is a German adverb and filler word often used in conversation akin to "so" or "therefore" in English. It’s used here to move the conversation forward.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is a definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It is in the neuter nominative or accusative singular form, agreeing with "Brandenburger Tor".</div><div><strong>Brandenburger Tor</strong> This is a proper noun referring to the Brandenburg Gate, a famous historical monument in Berlin, Germany. It’s a landmark name and therefore doesn’t require translation.</div><div><strong>an!</strong> This is a separable prefix attached to the verb "sehen" in the imperative form, completing the phrasal verb "ansehen", which means "to look at" or "to watch". In the imperative, it’s placed at the end of the sentence for emphasis.</div>'];